Barrel and forend easily separates from the action and buttstock by pushing a recessed lever, twisting the halves, and pulling them apart. Reassembly is the reverse of takedown. The friction fit lockup of the assembly joint is simple to adjust, but will rarely need adjustment after the first reassembly. Lockup is secure and repeatable ensuring an accurate return to zero - even when receiver mounted optics are used. Shipped in a ballistic nylon backpack-style case that features internal sleeves that hold the separated rifle halves, and external pockets with MOLLE webbing that provide extra storage. Padded, single-shoulder strap. Gun features include a black synthetic stock and forearm, an 18.50 inch stainless steel barrel with six grooves and a 1:16 inch right hand rifle twist. Clear matte finish. Adjustable rear sight and gold bead front sight. Ten round rotary magazine included. Weighs 4.67 pounds and is 37 inches long when assembled with each half being less than 20.25 inches when disassembled.

title: For Sale:  * Tula * Mosin Nagant and ammo - Prepper Special !!!
postcontent:
I recently had a few people contact me asking when I will post some of my Mosins for sale. Well, I've been kind of busy but I think I will pull a few out for you guys. I will only keep this ad up for a couple of weeks or so. After that they are all going back into storage. I might sell a few more towards the end of the year or in 2016 if you miss out on these. Actually, I will probably sell out of my round Tulas this time (I only have a few) so this is probably your only shot at getting one. I've seen what is coming down the pike and the Mosins that are currently commercially available look like sh*t! If you ever wanted to own a nice one for a reasonable price now is your chance.

Here is a copy of the ad I posted in March so I don't have to retype everything:

All my Izzy's are gone and since I have a few people asking I decided to put several more desirable / rare Tula's up for sale. I don't know what the production numbers were for a round receiver Tula but you hardly ever see one. I know after all these years of collecting I was only able to get my hands on a few (gotta love those big Russian stars on the receivers). These are mostly pre-war rifles (1938-1940) but likely saw battle. There are a few with rareish BRASS hand guard ends and a couple with nice factory repairs (always a plus for collectors - adds to the mystique). As always, all numbers match. First come / first served on getting to hand pick the best from the lot. If you buy a rifle I will throw in a 440 round spam can of silver tip milsurp ammo for $125. Yes, you might find a cheaper Mosin but it is well worth a few extra $$$ to get to hand pick one that you get to see instead of using mail order, paying for shipping, paying an FFL fee, and then finding out it was ran over by a tank in 1945 and is horrible looking. My rifles look great and all are still packed in cosmoline by the Russians who were waiting for WWIII to begin. Ask around, people know I have a quality collection. I will only sell a few rifles so make sure you jump on this. All rifles have matching numbers (including the bayonet !!!), a cleaning kit, and an oil/solvent canteen. Prices are extremely FIRM.

*** Oh, if you do not put I LOVE MOSIN somewhere in your email to me I will NOT reply. This is to keep the spam down. Again, if you do not put I LOVE MOSIN somewhere in your email to me I will NOT reply. ***

***** NOTE - I am looking for used 7.62x54r brass for reloading. If you shoot brass ammo please keep it instead of throwing it away and drop an email to me. I will buy it from you OR trade it for unfired military surplus rounds (silver tip). *****

If you cannot decide which rifle to pick my assistant will be happy to help you.

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG 18 - 12 Gauge
postcontent: The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.Caliber 12 gauge 3”Barrel length 18.5"Total capacity 6+6+1Weight empty 6.9lbsWeight loaded 8.5lbsLength 26.1"Height 7"MSRP $990.00
